==English==
{{wikipedia}}
===Etymology===
From Yuwaalaraay (a dialect of Gamilaraay) ''[[malga]]''.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈmʌlgə/}} (''UK'')
*{{IPA|/ˈməʉlɡə/ [ˈmɔʊlɡɐ]}} (''Australia'')

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Any of a number of small [[acacia]] trees, especially ''Acacia aneura'', forming dense scrub in dry inland areas of Australia.
# (''colloquial'') Land covered with such vegetation; the [[outback]].
#:*'''1901''': I'd forgotten for a moment you are not all '''mulga'''-bred — Jack Mathieu, ‘That Day at Boiling Downs’ (''Australian Ballads & Short Stories'', Penguin 2003, p. 263)
# Something made from the wood of a mulga tree.
# A [[mulga wire]].

